parameters.name: handle
parameters.description: Your user or team handle

parameters.name: endpoint_slug
parameters.description: The name of the endpoint as slug

parameters.name: allow_partial_results
parameters.description:
This enables returning a query result that was too large and only a partial result is
available. By default allow_partial_results is set to false and a failed state is returned.

parameters.name: columns
parameters.description:
Specifies a comma-separated list of column names to return. If omitted, all columns are included.
Tip: use this to limit the result to specific columns, reducing datapoints cost of the call.

parameters.name: filters
parameters.description:
Expression to filter out rows from the results to return. This expression is similar to
a SQL WHERE clause. More details about it in the Filtering section of the doc.
This parameter is incompatible with sample_count.

parameters.name: ignore_max_datapoints_per_request
parameters.description:
There is a default 250,000 datapoints limit to make sure you don't accidentally spend all
your credits in one call. To ignore the max limit, you can add
ignore_max_datapoints_per_request=true

parameters.name: limit
parameters.description:
Limit number of rows to return. This together with 'offset' allows easy pagination through
results in an incremental and efficient way. This parameter is incompatible
with sampling (sample_count).

parameters.name: offset
parameters.description:
Offset row number to start (inclusive, first row means offset=0) returning results
from. This together with 'limit' allows easy pagination through results in an
incremental and efficient way. This parameter is incompatible with sampling (sample_count).

parameters.name: sample_count
parameters.description:
Number of rows to return from the result by sampling the data. This is useful when you
want to get a uniform sample instead of the entire result. If the result has less
than the sample count, the entire result is returned. Note that this will return a
randomized sample, so not every call will return the same result. This parameter is
incompatible with `offset`, `limit`, and `filters` parameters.

parameters.name: sort_by
parameters.description:
Expression to define the order in which the results should be returned. This expression
is similar to a SQL ORDER BY clause. More details about it in the Sorting section of the doc.

Unique identifier for the pipeline execution. Use this ID to check the status

query_parameters.description: SQL Query parameters in json key-value pairs. Each parameter is to be provided in key-value pairs. This enables you to execute a parameterized query with the provided values for your parameter keys.

pipeline_execution_id.description:
Unique identifier for the pipeline execution. Use this ID to check the status
and retrieve results of the pipeline execution.

performance.description: The performance engine tier the execution will be run on

column_names.description: Names of the columns in the result set.

column_types.description: Types of the columns in the result set.

datapoint_count.description:
Results cell count is used for billing/pricing plans
here we expose the these values to the user, so that they can track their costs

execution_time_millis.description: Time in milliseconds that the query took to execute.

pending_time_millis.description: Time in milliseconds that the query was pending before execution.

result_set_bytes.description:
ResultSetBytes represents the raw data bytes returned by the SQL execution engine, it includes:
 + total nr of bytes used on 1 line with all the column names (the header of the result set)
 + total nr of bytes for all the row values (the result set of rows)

it doesn't include overheads such as the presence of column names for every row in the JSON result type.
it also doesn't include opmitizations such as compression

row_count.description: Number of rows in the result set for the current page of results.

total_result_set_bytes.description: Total number of bytes in the result set. This doesn't include the json representation overhead.

total_row_count.description: Number of rows in the result set for the entire result set.

cancelled_at.description: Timestamp of when the query execution was cancelled, if applicable.

error.description: In case the execution had an error, this object will contain the error details

execution_ended_at.description: Timestamp of when the query execution ended.

execution_id.description: Unique identifier for the execution of the query and corresponding result.

execution_started_at.description: Timestamp of when the query execution started.

expires_at.description: Timestamp of when the query result expires.

is_execution_finished.description: Whether the state of the query execution is terminal. This can be used for polling purposes.

max_inflight_interactive_executions.description: Number of interactive executions this customer can have running in parallel

max_inflight_interactive_reached.description:
Total number of interactive executions this user has submitted which are still in progress
only set to > 0 if the user has reached the limit of concurrent interactive executions

result_metadata.description: Metadata about the execution of the query, including details like column names, row counts, and execution times.

state.description: The state of the query execution.

submitted_at.description: Timestamp of when the query was submitted.

error.description: Error message if the pipeline execution failed

node_executions.description: List of node executions in the pipeline.

status.description: Overall status of the pipeline execution

pipeline.description: The pipeline definition containing nodes to execute

is_archived.description:
Indicates if the query is archived.
Archived queries cannot be executed.

is_private.description: Indicates if the query is private.

is_unsaved.description: Indicates if the query is unsaved.

parameters.description: The parameters that can modify the execution of the sql.

query_engine.description: The query engine used to execute the query.

query_id.description: The unique ID of the query

version.description: Version of the query, gets incremented every time the query is updated.

nodes.description: List of nodes in the pipeline. Nodes are executed in dependency order.

name.description: Name of the materialized view to refresh

performance.description: The performance engine tier the refresh will be run on. Can be either `medium` or `large`.

error.description: Error message if the refresh failed

execution_id.description: Unique identifier of the execution, if available

status.description: Status of the materialized view refresh

dependencies.description: List of node IDs that this node depends on. Nodes are executed in dependency order.

id.description: Unique identifier of the node in the pipeline

materialized_view_refresh.description: Materialized view refresh node configuration. Required if this node refreshes a materialized view.

query_execution.description: Query execution node configuration. Required if this node executes a query.

id.description: Unique identifier of the node in the pipeline

materialized_view_refresh_status.description: Status of the materialized view refresh, if this node is a materialized view refresh node

query_execution_status.description: Status of the query execution, if this node is a query execution node

performance.description: The performance engine tier the execution will be run on. Can be either `medium` or `large`.

query_id.description: Unique identifier of the query to execute

query_parameters.description: SQL Query parameters in json key-value pairs. Each parameter is to be provided in key-value pairs. This enables you to execute a parameterized query with the provided values for your parameter keys.

error.description: Error message, if the execution failed

execution_id.description: Unique identifier of the execution, if available

metadata.description:
Metadata about the execution of the query, including details like column names,
row counts, and execution times.

rows.description:
A list of rows. A row is dictionary of key-value pairs returned by the query,
each pair corresponding to a column

update_type.description: The type of update operation from Trino (e.g., "SET SESSION")

message.description: A descriptive message about the error.

metadata.description: Metadata about the syntax error that occurred, if applicable.

type.description: The type of error that occurred.

cancelled_at.description: Timestamp of when the query execution was cancelled, if applicable.

error.description: In case the execution had an error, this object will contain the error details

execution_ended_at.description: Timestamp of when the query execution ended.

execution_id.description: Unique identifier for the execution of the query.

execution_started_at.description: Timestamp of when the query execution started.

expires_at.description: Timestamp of when the query result expires.

is_execution_finished.description: Whether the state of the query execution is terminal. This can be used for polling purposes.

next_offset.description: Offset that can be used to retrieve the next page of results.

next_uri.description: URI that can be used to fetch the next page of results.

result.description: The object containing the results and metadata of the query execution

state.description: The state of the query execution.

submitted_at.description: Timestamp of when the query was submitted.

column.description: The column number at which the syntax error occurred.

line.description: The line number at which the syntax error occurred in the query.

type.description: ColumnType is a json.RawMessage so that we can support objects like Array and Struct.

nullable.description: Whether the column can contain null values

purged_at.description: ISO 8601 timestamp of when table was purged

table_size_bytes.description: Size of the table in bytes

next_offset.description: Offset for next page of results

type.description: Type of entity that created the table

query_id.description: The unique ID of the query that was updated
